<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet >
    <title>GR-5 Modeling Systems</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>Complete all four problems to get M. Complete any three problems to get P.</p>
  </introduction>
  <page>
      <p>A pet shelter mixes two brands of kibble, Brand <m>A</m> and Brand <m>B</m>, to create a 
        daily feeding blend for its dogs. The blend must satisfy minimum nutritional requirements 
        for protein and iron. Each cup of Brand <m>A</m> provides 5 grams of protein and 2 milligrams 
        of iron. Each cup of Brand <m>B</m> provides 3 grams of protein and 6 milligrams of iron. 
        The daily requirements demand at least 30 grams of protein and at least 24 milligrams of 
        iron. The shelter wants to minimize the total number of cups fed to keep the dogs at a 
        healthy caloric intake.</p>
    <exercise workspace="1.5in"><statement><p>Set up a system of linear inequalities whose graph 
        would represent all possible combinations of foods <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> that satisfy the 
        constraints.</p></statement></exercise>
    <exercise workspace="2.5in"><statement><p>Find the solution region. Be sure to give a complete graph.</p></statement></exercise>
  </page>
  <page>
    <exercise workspace="1in"><statement><p>Setup the objective function.</p></statement></exercise>
    <exercise workspace="2.5in"><statement><p>Find the minimum number of cups of each brand that 
      the shelter can use to meet the nutritional requirements.</p></statement></exercise>
  </page>
</worksheet>